    'html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Every GLP-1 weight loss drug on the market requires weekly injections. Semaglutide, tirzepatide, retatrutide: all needles. For millions of people who could benefit from these drugs but won't inject themselves, that's a barrier. Orforglipron from Eli Lilly aims to remove it entirely. It's a once-daily pill that activates the GLP-1 receptor with no injection required.</p>

<h2>Why an Oral GLP-1 Was So Hard to Make</h2>

<p>Peptides are proteins, and proteins get destroyed in the stomach. Gastric acid and digestive enzymes break peptide bonds apart, which is why insulin (discovered in 1921) still requires injection over a century later. Making a GLP-1 agonist that survives the GI tract and gets absorbed into the bloodstream is a significant pharmaceutical challenge.</p>

<p>Oral semaglutide (Rybelsus) was the first attempt to solve this. It uses a special absorption enhancer (SNAC) that temporarily raises local stomach pH and promotes transcellular absorption. It works, but with significant limitations: it must be taken on a completely empty stomach with only 4 ounces of water, then you must wait 30 minutes before eating, drinking, or taking other medications. Compliance is difficult, and the oral bioavailability is roughly 1% of the injected dose.</p>

<p>Orforglipron takes a fundamentally different approach. It's not a peptide at all. It's a small molecule, a non-peptide compound that activates the GLP-1 receptor through a different binding site. Because it's not a peptide, it isn't degraded by stomach acid or digestive enzymes. It absorbs through the gut like a conventional pill.</p>

<h2>Phase 2 Trial Results</h2>

<p>The Phase 2 trial of orforglipron, published in the New England Journal of Medicine in 2023, enrolled 272 adults with obesity or overweight. Participants were randomized to various doses or placebo for 36 weeks.</p>

<p>At the highest dose (45mg once daily), orforglipron produced 14.7% average body weight loss. The 36mg dose produced 12.6% loss. Both results are clinically meaningful and approach injectable semaglutide's efficacy, though in a shorter trial duration.</p>

<p>Like injectable GLP-1 agonists, weight loss was ongoing at the end of the trial period, suggesting the plateau hadn't been reached. Longer trials might show higher total weight loss. Metabolic improvements paralleled the weight loss: HbA1c decreased, fasting glucose improved, and lipid profiles shifted favorably.</p>

<h2>Side Effects: Similar to Injectable GLP-1s</h2>

<p>The side effect profile mirrors what we see with injectable GLP-1 agonists: nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, and decreased appetite are the most common complaints. GI side effects occurred in roughly 35-45% of patients at higher doses, predominantly during the dose escalation period.</p>

<p>Discontinuation rates due to side effects were slightly higher than injectable GLP-1 trials (approximately 10-15% vs 4-7% for injectable tirzepatide). This may reflect the daily dosing (constant GLP-1 stimulation) versus weekly injection (which produces more pulsatile exposure).</p>

<p>No new safety signals emerged beyond what's expected from the GLP-1 class. The thyroid C-cell tumor concern (from rodent data with GLP-1 agonists) applies equally.</p>

<h2>Advantages Over Injectable GLP-1 Drugs</h2>

<p><strong>No injections:</strong> The obvious one. For needle-averse patients (which surveys suggest is 20-30% of the potential GLP-1 population), an oral option removes the primary barrier to treatment.</p>

<p><strong>No cold chain:</strong> Injectable GLP-1 drugs require refrigeration. Orforglipron is a pill that stores at room temperature. This eliminates cold chain logistics for pharmacies, patients, and travelers.</p>

<p><strong>Simpler manufacturing:</strong> Small molecules are cheaper to manufacture than peptides. If this translates to lower pricing (not guaranteed but plausible), it could dramatically improve access. The current $1,000+/month cost of injectable GLP-1 drugs is a major barrier.</p>

<p><strong>No absorption enhancer requirements:</strong> Unlike oral semaglutide (Rybelsus), orforglipron doesn't require special timing with food and water. It can be taken with or without food, which is a meaningful improvement in real-world compliance.</p>

<h2>Where Things Stand</h2>

<p>Orforglipron is in Phase 3 clinical trials as of 2026. Eli Lilly has multiple large-scale trials running simultaneously for obesity, type 2 diabetes, and metabolic complications. The Phase 3 program includes thousands of patients across numerous sites, which should provide robust efficacy and safety data.</p>

<p>FDA approval is not expected before late 2026 or 2027, depending on trial completion and review timelines. If approved, it would be the first truly practical oral GLP-1 agonist, a pill that works like semaglutide but without the needle.</p>

<h2>What This Means for the Peptide Landscape</h2>

<p>Orforglipron represents a broader trend: the evolution from injectable peptides to small molecule oral drugs that target the same receptors. If a pill can activate GLP-1 receptors as effectively as semaglutide, the convenience advantage shifts dramatically.</p>

<p>This doesn't make injectable GLP-1 drugs obsolete. Injection provides more precise dosing, more predictable absorption, and (based on current data) slightly higher efficacy. But for the general population seeking weight management, a once-daily pill with 15% weight loss and no needles changes the calculation entirely.</p>

<p>The injectable peptide space will likely continue for people who need maximum efficacy (tirzepatide and retatrutide offer higher weight loss than orforglipron's current data), specialized medical applications, and combination protocols that require precise dosing. But orforglipron could become the first-line treatment for the majority of patients, with injectables reserved for those who need more aggressive intervention.</p>
